-- Regression: REG-02 crash-canary for IRON_HIR_STMT_SPAWN.
--
-- **Motivating Incident.** Phase 37-02's collect_mono_enums_node
-- walker crashed on if/elif/else lowering because its locally-shadowed
-- struct typedef omitted elif fields. The same walker-incompleteness
-- class can re-emerge for any other statement kind. Spawn is a
-- concurrency-primitive statement that carries a named-thread label
-- plus a body block, and the body is expected to run on a separate
-- stack. Walker cases that fail to recurse into the spawn body
-- silently drop the task's work from the lowered LIR -- and because
-- the main thread still waits for the spawn handle, the bug manifests
-- as a hang or a zero-valued await result, not a compile error.
--
-- **Layout Diagram.** Iron_SpawnStmt carries
--   { span, kind, label_string, body }
-- Walker cases that fail to recurse into `body` produce an empty
-- thread task that returns the default value and silently wrong
-- output. Walker cases that mis-type `body` can also crash during
-- LIR emission.
--
-- **Fix Summary.** Phase 67-08 added this fixture as a REG-02 crash
-- canary. Uses a single spawn-with-await pattern (see
-- tests/integration/spawn_await_return.iron for the canonical
-- template) to produce a deterministic integer output. CI integration:
-- runs in both Debug and Release via Phase 66-04's build-and-test-
-- release job.
--
-- **Severity.** H (regression potential) -- spawn is exercised by
-- every threaded Iron program, and a walker regression would produce
-- silently wrong output under normal execution.

func compute(n: Int) -> Int {
  var sum = 0
  var i = 0
  while i < n {
    sum = sum + i
    i = i + 1
  }
  return sum
}

func main() {
  val h = spawn("worker") {
    return compute(10)
  }
  val r = await h
  println("result: {r}")
}
